PrefacePreface
'Go Green' a series of books on Environmental Education (EVS) is based on 
the EVS syllabus as prescribed by the N.C.E.R.T according to NEP and NCF.
To enable the students to realize their holistic potential in the process of 
learning, we have laid emphasis on the major skills that are to be 
developed through EVS. These skills include environmental sensitivity i.e. 
awareness, activity, projects, discussionsscientific skills
 and 
.
For the development of these skills the learners need to be aware of their 
surroundings and become keen observer. They should have the spirit of 
enquiry, be able to express their views and exhibit creativity and 
originality in doing activities and projects.
Keeping these needs of today's learners in mind we have prepared this 
series of EVS books.
These books will also enable the teachers to develop the skills in students 
as well as assess their learning process.
Any suggestions for the betterment of the book shall be thankfully 
acknowledged and incorporated in the subsequent editions.

Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWOur FamilyUnit–I : We and Our Family1
Environmental Studies-406As you learnt in class 3, a family consists of people who live together and are 
related to each other. A family can be big or small, joint or nuclear. In this 
chapter we shall learn about the relations among the members of a family and 
the changes that occur in it over a period of time.
StarterA. 
Paste a picture of your family when you were a baby.
B.

What are the differences that you note in your parents and yourself in the 
two pictures?
The Relation Among the Members of a FamilyThe members of a family may be related to each 
other as follows—
 
(a) 
When a boy and a girl marry each 
other, they form a family. They are 
called husband and wife.

(b) 
Children born to parents 
become a part of the parent's 
family.
(c) 
Some people do not have children of their 
own. Such people accept children into their 
families who are not born to them. Such 
children become a part of the family. This is 
called adoption.
Changes in a FamilyMany changes take place in the structure of a family over a period of time. It may be 
due to some of the reasons given below.
! 
Marriage– When a son or a daughter of a family marries, a new member in 
the form of a daughter-in-law or son-in-law joins the family.
!
Birth– 
 
When a child is born he/she becomes a part of the family.
!
Job transfers
 
– Some members of a family might have to stay separately as 
they get jobs in different cities. This causes change in the structure of a 
family.
If we look at our own families, we will see changes that have taken place over time. 
Some of our family members would have grown older or new members would have 
been born. We all go through this cycle of change and growth. Our parents too 
Your Mother as a ChildHave you ever seen the pictures of your mother when she was a young girl? As a 
young girl, she would have been a good dancer or a good athlete. But, over the 
years, she has changed a lot.

Need of a familyA family is the foundation of society. We get love, warmth and protection from our 
family. Elders earn money to fulfill our requirements. Without our families, our life 
would become very difficult. 
Extended Family & Family GatheringsKirti is the only child of her parents. Thus, she belongs to a small family. Her 
grandparents, uncles-aunts and their children are her extended family. They do not 
live under one roof but meet each other on occasions like wedding, festivals, 
birthday parties etc. and have fun together.
Maternal Relatives– Kirti's mother belongs to a big family which has her 
grandparents, uncles, aunts and cousins. They live together happily. The relatives 
from mother's side are called maternal relatives e.g. grand parents (nana and 
nani), Uncles (mama, mausa), aunts (mami, mausi) and cousins (children of mausi 
and mami). The relatives from the father's side are called paternal relatives e.g 
grandparents (dada and dadi), uncles (chacha , taya) aunts (bua and chachi) and 
cousins (children of chachi, bua and tayi.)(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-408

We all have a mouth to eat food and to drink water. In human beings, the 
mouth mainly consists of a tongue and teeth. They both have special

! They give shape to our face. 
 
! They help to make our speech clear.
! They help us to chew our food properlyTeethThe food that we eat can be digested easily only when it is chewed well.
1.
2.
Starter(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-413

Types of TeethOur teeth have different shapes to help us eat different types of food. Sometimes, 
we need to grind our food and sometimes, it is to be torn or cut into smaller pieces. 
We have four kinds of teeth in our permanent set.
Human beings grow two sets of teeth during their life time: (A) milk teeth and (B) 
permanent teeth.
Milk teeth– Babies do not have any teeth in the beginning. The first tooth comes 
out when the baby is about six months old. By the age of two and a half year, the 
baby has a complete set of 20 teeth. These are called milk teeth. These teeth begin 
to fall by the age of 6, so they are also called temporary teeth.
Permanent teeth– When milk teeth fall off, they are replaced by new and stronger 
teeth. By the age of 12 years, all the milk teeth are replaced by a set of 28 teeth. 
These are called permanent teeth.
Between the age of 12 and 21, four more teeth grow. These are called wisdom 
teeth. Finally, the adult has a set of 32 permanent teeth.
1. Incisors (Biting teeth)– The four front teeth in each jaw are 
called incisors. Thus, we have eight incisors. They are chisel 
shaped and used for cutting or biting the food.
2. Canines (Tearing teeth)– We have a pointed tooth called 
canine on either side of the incisors. Thus, we have four 
canines, two in upper jaw and two in lower jaw. These teeth 
are used to tear the food.
3. Premolars (Chewing teeth)– After the canines on each side, 
we have two flat and broad teeth which are used to crack or 
chew the food. These are called premolars. They are eight in 
number (four in each jaw).
Environmental Studies-414

You 
 KnowMust 
4. Molars (Grinding Teeth)– After the premolars on each 
side, there are three molars. They are broad with points 
and grooves. Thus, there are twelve molars (six in each 
jaw) that help in grinding the food.
All these teeth work together to break the food 
into small pieces. This helps us to swallow and 
digest our food easily.
Teeth are even harder than our bones.
(Knowledge)Tooth DecayCare of TeethWe must take care of our teeth. If they are not cleaned properly, a sticky layer of 
food particles is formed on them. Due to this, our teeth look yellow and dirty and 
give out a bad smell. After sometime, bacteria grow in our mouth. These bacteria 
produce an acid which makes holes or cavities in the teeth. This is called tooth 
decay. 
To keep our teeth healthy, we should follow some good dental habits–
! We should brush our teeth twice a day, once in the morning and once before 
going to bed.
! We should avoid sticky food like sweets, chocolates, ice-creams. They spoil 
our teeth.
! We should eat fresh fruits and leafy vegetables. They make our teeth and 
gums strong.
! We should rinse our mouth with water every time we eat something.
! We should visit a dentist once in six months.
Environmental Studies-415

Teeth of AnimalsAnimals also have teeth which help them to chew their food.
Herbivores such as cows, horse, camels, deer, sheep etc. have flat teeth in front and 
broad teeth at the back. The front teeth help them to bite grass and leaves of 
plants. The back teeth are suited for chewing and grinding. They do not have 
canines because they do not need them.
Carnivores (flesh eating animals) like lion, tiger, cats, dogs etc. have very sharp 
pointed canines which they use for tearing the flesh of their prey.
TongueOur tongue is a muscular organ which helps us to 
move food in the mouth and swallow it. It also 
helps us to speak.
The upper surface of the tongue has tiny bumps 
on it which contain groups of taste buds. Each of 
these taste buds has tiny nerves which send 
messages to the brain and immediately the brain 
tells us what we are eating.
The taste buds are located on different parts of the tongue. The tip of the tongue is 
sensitive to sweet taste and the back is sensitive to bitter taste. The sides of the 
tongue are sensitive to sour and salty tastes. Hence, our tongue helps us to identify 
four basic tastes-sweet, salty, sour and bitter.
Rodents (gnawing animals) like rabbit, squirrel, rat etc. gnaw at seeds, fruits and 
nuts. They have two pairs of sharp razor-like teeth to gnaw on nuts and seeds.
Reptiles 
fish 
and 
have all teeth of nearly the same size and shape. They use them to 
catch their prey. They replace their teeth continuously.
